The Booker Prize is Britain's literary event of

"The prize has become internationally known, and the worldwide demand for the winning book, in English and translations, is spectacular," said Shaw.
Each juror reads every book submitted, lists about six favorites and meets the other jurors to select and announce six finalists.
This year's finalists: Beryl Bainbridge "An Awfully Big Adventure," A.S. Byatt "Possession," Penelope Fitzgerald "The Gate of Angels," John McGahern "Amongst Women," Brian Moore "Lies of Silence" and Mordecai Richler "Solomon Gursky Was Here."
